There are several sets of operations that have to occur, we have multiplication, division, addition, and subtraction. In order to solve this expression we must know the order of operations (PEMDAS). We can simply use the acronym for each kind of function. Parentheses, Exponents, multiplication, division, addition and subtraction. This means that if there are no parentheses are to perform operations on the outer level, then we use exponents, if there is any simplification that occurs within parentheses, it's the next level that we work on. We follow the order of math functions.
Also when we are taking away brackets, the terms also follow the PEMDAS paradigm.
So first of all, let's see what our priorities are. There are no Parentheses. We could try to take the simplification of a set of brackets right, but there's none. Exponents are there as well. Then we still have multiplication and division. When we have multiplication or division, addition or subtraction there are symbols which different mean. There can be addition, subtraction, inequality, greater than, greater than or equal to, less than, less than or equal to, for example less than or equal to and greater than equal to. So that represents symbols that cannot be neglected here. That's an inequality. There's the symbol for an inequality sign. We work on any multiplication or division with the highest precedence first and essentially simplify it. If we multiply or divide the smallest numbers that come first, it's the lowest priority measure. With addition and subtraction we have to identify the smallest symbols. Once we have gone through all of the sub-structure, we can simplify all of our stuff that resides in parentheses.
So let's start with $14\div 2\cdot 9$. What is $14\div 2$? It's 7. We can prime factorize $14$ to $7\cdot 2$. The question is of "before the prime factorizations," so the part I will highlight will stay because it's before the equal sign.
\[-\left(\color{green}{\require{cancel}
       \boxed{7}}\color{black}{\cdot 2}\cdot 9-60+3\cdot 9\right)\]
